                        <bindingDesc>
                                 <binding contemporary="Ethiopian true">
                                   <p>The manuscript is bound using the traditional Ethiopian technique. Holes were cut in the boards adjacent to the existing first sewing station
                                     for the thread to pass through and the position of sewing holes was marked on the spine of the quires, but they have been never been pierced.
                                     It was decided instead to relocate the sewing station to a higher position, cutting new holes in the boards. The present binding is the first binding received by the manuscript.</p>
                                     <decoNote xml:id="b1" type="bindingMaterial">
                                       The book is bound in <material key="wood">wooden</material> boards.
                                     </decoNote>
                                     <decoNote xml:id="b2" type="Boards">
                                       The boards are flush with the bookblock and have shallow external bevels. The grain runs vertically.
                                       The inner surface and the edges of the boards are rough.
                                     </decoNote>
                                     <decoNote xml:id="b4" type="SewingStations">2</decoNote>
                                     <decoNote xml:id="b5">
                                       Chainstitch sewing on two sewing stations (one pair); S-plied thread.
                                       In the first quire, between the sewing stations, there is one length of thread. In the rest of the quires there are double lengths.
                                       The sewing is closed in the last quire, by knotting the ends of the thread to each other.
                                     </decoNote>
                                     <decoNote xml:id="b6" type="Spine">
                                       The small holes close to the tail of the quires are probably what remains of quire tackets.
                                     </decoNote>
                                 </binding>
                             </bindingDesc>


